<h2>The Question</h2>

<p>The Web Everything backlog carries <strong>two near-redundant axes</strong> on every item:
<code>type</code> (<code>idea</code> / <code>issue</code> / <code>decision</code>) and <code>workItem</code>
(<code>story</code> / <code>epic</code> / <code>task</code>). A buildable item states its nature
<em>twice</em> — it is both <code>type: idea</code> <strong>and</strong> <code>workItem: story</code>.
Decision <a href="/backlog/466-collapse-backlog-type-workitem-into-one-kind-axis-retire-the/">#466</a>
asks: collapse the two into one <code>kind</code> axis (<code>story | epic | task | decision</code>),
or keep two axes and accept the redundancy?</p>

<p>This page surveys how mature issue trackers model the relationship between an item's
<strong>nature</strong>, its <strong>hierarchy role</strong>, and its <strong>effort/size</strong>, to
ground that call before it is made.</p>


<h2>Why this is a real question (current state)</h2>

<p>Tooling shows the <code>type</code> axis is mostly cosmetic, while only <code>decision</code> is
load-bearing:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Tiering treats <code>idea</code> and <code>issue</code> identically</strong> — both map to
  Tier A in the loader (<code>src/_data/backlog.js</code>). <code>decision</code> is the only type with
  distinct behaviour (Tier B + the fork-shape validator).</li>
  <li><strong><code>idea</code> vs <code>issue</code> is a badge colour + a filter order</strong> — the
  docs claim <code>issue</code> ranks above <code>idea</code> in selection, but the tooling never
  implements that ordering (vestigial).</li>
  <li><strong><code>workItem</code> drives real machinery</strong> — <code>story</code> requires a
  Fibonacci <code>size</code>; <code>task</code> forbids one; <code>epic</code> rolls up children. This
  is the agile burndown axis and is genuinely load-bearing.</li>
  <li><strong>A fourth type (<code>review</code>) just collapsed with zero residue</strong> — a factual
  verification became an <code>issue</code>, an open judgment a <code>decision</code>. That it named no
  fourth nature is evidence the type axis is thin. (The enum string <code>review</code> has since been
  removed from the validator set, completing the retirement; <code>type: review</code> now fails the gate.)</li>
</ul>


<h2>How mature trackers model nature × role × size</h2>

