<p><strong>The cross-tool invariant:</strong> every mature tracker keeps exactly <em>one</em> structural
type/kind axis (folding nature and hierarchy-role together, as Jira does with Epic+Bug), holds
<em>size/effort</em> as a separate orthogonal field, and demotes any residual fix-vs-feature flavour to
an <em>optional label</em> — never a second required nature field. WE's <code>type</code> +
<code>workItem</code> double-statement is the configuration nobody else runs, because the two axes are
correlated, not orthogonal.</p>


<h2>Architecture reading (classification)</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Layer:</strong> internal repo tooling (the standard's own backlog), not a shipped WE
  standard. WE never mandates conventions; this is project-management machinery, so the decision is a
  local data-model call, not a protocol or intent.</li>
  <li><strong>Orthogonality test (the crux):</strong> <code>type∈{idea,issue}</code> and
  <code>workItem∈{story,task}</code> are <strong>not independent</strong> — they co-vary (an idea is a
  buildable story; an issue is a small fix-task). Two correlated axes measuring the same thing are a
  redundancy, so <em>merging</em> them is the honest model. The genuinely-orthogonal axis,
  <code>size</code>, stays separate — honouring the bias toward separation exactly where it applies.</li>
  <li><strong>Most-permissive default:</strong> the residual fix-vs-feature nuance needs no required
  field — the existing free-form <code>tags</code> array already absorbs a <code>fix</code> /
  <code>feature</code> tag for anyone who wants it, with zero new machinery. So the fix/feature
  distinction is not a fork; it is "drop the required field, keep the open tag axis."</li>
</ul>


<h2>Recommendation</h2>

<p><strong>Unify into one <code>kind</code> axis</strong> (<code>story | epic | task | decision</code>),
keep <code>size</code> separate, and let <code>tags</code> carry any fix-vs-feature flavour. This matches
the universal tracker model, removes the double-statement, and preserves the only load-bearing
behaviours (sizing on <code>story</code>; Tier-B + fork-validation on <code>decision</code>). The cost is
a one-pass migration across the backlog files and the loader / readiness / validator / scaffold / render
/ docs — real, but mechanical once the field map is fixed.</p>

<p>The survey moved the confidence on this from "lean" to "strong": no surveyed tracker validates the
two-axis alternative, and the fix/feature sub-question dissolves into the existing tag axis rather than
standing as its own fork.</p>


